SIMPLE: precaution
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Precaution
<hw>Pre*cau"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>pr⟦eacute⟧cation</ets>, L. <ets>praecautio</ets>, fr.
<ets>praecavere</ets>, <ets>praecautum</ets>, to guard against
beforehand; <ets>prae</ets> before + <ets>cavere</ets> be on one's
guard. See <er>Pre-</er>, and <er>Caution</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Previous caution or care; caution previously employed to prevent
mischief or secure good; <as>as, his life was saved by
<ex>precaution</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They [ancient philosophers] treasured up their supposed
discoveries with miserable <qex>precaution</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>J. H.
Newman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A measure taken beforehand to ward off evil or
secure good or success; a precautionary act; <as>as, to take
<ex>precautions</ex> against accident</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Precaution</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Precaution
<hw>Pre*cau"tion</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>pr⟦eacute⟧cautionner</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To warn or
caution beforehand.</def> <rj><au>Locke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1126 --></p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To take precaution against.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Precautional</ent>⟦br⟧
